## Alert Fatigue Prevention

### Alert Design Principles

| Principle | Application |
|-----------|-------------|
| Alert on symptoms, not causes | "Error rate high" not "Database connection failed" |
| One alert, one owner | No orphan alerts |
| Actionable | Every alert has a runbook action |
| Thresholds tuned | Not too sensitive, not too slow |
| Consolidate | Avoid 10 alerts for same incident |

### Severity Levels

| Severity | Response Time | Example |
|----------|---------------|---------|
| Critical | Immediate (page) | Service down, data loss risk |
| High | 15 minutes | Degraded performance, partial outage |
| Medium | 1 hour | Non-critical failure |
| Low | Next business day | Capacity warning, cleanup |

### Alert Routing

```yaml
# Route by severity and service
routes:
  - match:
      severity: critical
    receiver: pagerduty-primary
  - match:
      severity: high
    receiver: slack-incidents
  - match:
      service: api
    receiver: api-team
```

### Alert Tuning Checklist

- [ ] No alert fires during normal operation
- [ ] Thresholds based on baseline (not arbitrary)
- [ ] Suppress during planned maintenance
- [ ] Review and retire stale alerts quarterly
- [ ] Consolidate similar alerts

